\description{
\code{psave()} constructs a model-averaged propensity score
\eqn{\bar e(X) = \sum_m \lambda_m \hat e_m(X)}: a convex combination of
candidate propensity score models whose mixing weights \eqn{\lambda} are
selected on a simplex grid to optimize a balance criterion -- by default the
weighted absolute standardized mean difference of a \strong{model-averaged
prognostic score} (the "Prog (Ave)" estimator of Kabata, Stuart and
Shintani 2024). The result is deliberately modest: a numeric score vector
designed to be handed to \code{\link[MatchIt:matchit]{MatchIt::matchit()}} as \code{distance}, or to
\code{\link[WeightIt:weightit]{WeightIt::weightit()}} as \code{ps}, with balance assessment via \pkg{cobalt}.
}
\details{
\subsection{Algorithm}{
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Candidate propensity scores.} Each learner in \code{ps.methods} is fit on
all \eqn{n} units and predicts \eqn{\hat e_m(X_i) = P(A_i = 1 \mid X_i)}
in-sample; each column is clipped to \code{clip} before averaging. Extra
user-supplied candidates given via \code{ps.append} are validated, clipped
identically, and appended AFTER the base candidates (from \code{ps.methods}
or \code{ps.matrix}), so the first-minimum tie-break favors the base set.
\item \strong{Model-averaged prognostic score.} Each learner in \code{prog.methods} is
fit on the \strong{untreated units only} and predicts \eqn{\hat g_k(0, X_i)}
for all \eqn{n} units; \code{prog.append} columns are appended after these
candidates. The mixing weights \eqn{\gamma} minimize the
unweighted untreated-set mean squared error
\deqn{\mathrm{MSE}(\gamma) = \mathrm{mean}_{i:A_i=0}\bigl(Y_i - \textstyle\sum_k \gamma_k \hat g_k(0, X_i)\bigr)^2}
over \code{simplex_grid(K, step)}; \eqn{\bar g = \sum_k \gamma_k \hat g_k}.
\item \strong{Model-averaged propensity score.} The mixing weights \eqn{\lambda}
minimize \code{criterion} over \code{simplex_grid(M, step)}, where each grid row
implies \eqn{\bar e_\lambda = \sum_m \lambda_m \hat e_m} and the weights
\eqn{W_i} below.
}
}

\subsection{Inverse-probability weights (exact supplement formulas)}{

With \eqn{\bar e_i} the averaged propensity score:
\deqn{\mathrm{ATT:}\quad W_i = 1 \; (A_i = 1), \qquad W_i = \bar e_i / (1 - \bar e_i) \; (A_i = 0);}
\deqn{\mathrm{ATE:}\quad W_i = 1 / \bar e_i \; (A_i = 1), \qquad W_i = 1 / (1 - \bar e_i) \; (A_i = 0).}
These are identical to \code{\link[WeightIt:get_w_from_ps]{WeightIt::get_w_from_ps()}} at the same estimand.
}

\subsection{Selection criteria}{

At each grid row \eqn{\lambda}:
\describe{
\item{\code{logloss}}{\eqn{-\mathrm{mean}\{A_i \log \bar e_i + (1 - A_i) \log(1 - \bar e_i)\}}
(finite by clipping).}
\item{\code{smd}}{the mean over covariate columns \eqn{j} of
\deqn{\mathrm{ASMD}_j = \Bigl| \frac{\sum_{A_i=1} W_i X_{ij}}{\sum_{A_i=1} W_i} - \frac{\sum_{A_i=0} W_i X_{ij}}{\sum_{A_i=0} W_i} \Bigr| / s_j,}
where \eqn{s_j} is the \strong{unweighted sample SD} of \eqn{X_j} in the
\code{s.d.denom} group (the treated group for both estimands, per the
paper's supplement).}
\item{\code{ks}}{the mean over covariates of the proper weighted-eCDF
Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic
\eqn{\sup_x |F^w_1(x) - F^w_0(x)|} with
\eqn{F^w_a(x) = \sum_{i:A_i=a} W_i 1(X_{ij} \le x) / \sum_{i:A_i=a} W_i};
for binary columns this equals the absolute difference in weighted
proportions.}
\item{\code{prog}}{the \eqn{\mathrm{ASMD}} formula applied to the single
column \eqn{\bar g} (\code{prog.target = "average"}) or \eqn{\hat g_k}
(\code{prog.target} names a learner). THE DEFAULT.}
}
When \code{prog.target} names a single prognostic candidate, \code{criterion.value}
is the weighted ASMD of that candidate's prognostic score, whereas the
\code{prog} column of the \code{diagnostics} table always refers to the
model-averaged prognostic score \eqn{\bar g}; the two values therefore
need not coincide, and \code{\link[=summary.psave]{summary.psave()}} prints a footnote to this effect.
Faithful to the published method, the \code{smd} and \code{prog} criteria standardize
\strong{all} columns -- including binary ones -- by the plain unweighted sample
SD (uniform sample-SD standardization; \code{bin.vars = FALSE} is passed to
\code{\link[cobalt:col_w_smd]{cobalt::col_w_smd()}} for every column). The display-oriented \code{balance}
component and \code{\link[=bal.tab.psave]{bal.tab.psave()}} use \pkg{cobalt}'s native conventions
instead; see \code{vignette("method-details", "psAve")}.
}

\subsection{Simplex grid and tie-breaking}{

Both grids are enumerated by \code{\link[=simplex_grid]{simplex_grid()}} in integer arithmetic
(every valid grid point is present by construction) in a documented order:
the first component descends from 1 to 0, then the second on the remainder,
and so on -- the first row puts all weight on the first candidate. Ties in
any argmin take the FIRST row attaining the minimum (within a 1e-9 relative
numerical tolerance), so ties favor learners listed earlier in
\code{ps.methods}/\code{prog.methods}; candidates appended via
\code{ps.append}/\code{prog.append} always come last and therefore lose ties to the
base candidates. The tolerance is deliberate: the criterion
values come from floating-point matrix algebra whose lowest-order bits can
differ across BLAS implementations, so an exact bitwise \code{which.min()}
would not be reproducible across machines, whereas the tolerant
first-minimum rule is. \code{gamma} always minimizes the unweighted
untreated-set MSE; these rules are fixed and not arguments.
}

\subsection{Why using the outcome does not bias the design}{

Prognostic models see the outcomes of \strong{untreated units only}, and the
criterion compares weighted \emph{covariate-like summaries} (the prognostic
score) between arms -- it never uses a treated-untreated outcome contrast
(Hansen 2008; Stuart, Lee and Leacy 2013). This is the same argument under
which prognostic-score balance diagnostics are recommended for propensity
score analyses; see \code{vignette("method-details", "psAve")}.
}

\subsection{Reproducibility}{

There is no \code{seed} argument: call \code{set.seed()} before \code{psave()} --
stochastic learners are \code{ranger} and \code{xgboost}. \code{info$learners} records the
resolved hyperparameters and engine package versions.
}

\subsection{Relation to other software}{

\link[WeightIt:method_super]{WeightIt::method_super} with \code{SL.method = "method.balance"} (Pirracchio
and Carone 2018) selects a SuperLearner combination by \emph{covariate} balance
and is weighting-only. \code{psave()} targets \emph{prognostic-score} balance on an
exhaustive simplex grid, and returns a score vector equally usable for
matching and weighting. See \link{psave-details} and
\code{vignette("method-details", "psAve")} for the differences from the paper's
reference implementation.
}
}
\examples{
if (requireNamespace("MatchIt", quietly = TRUE)) {
  data("lalonde", package = "MatchIt")

  # Paper-headline "Prog (Ave)", ATT. For speed, this example restricts the
  # candidate learners; the default is
  # ps.methods = prog.methods = c("glm", "rpart", "ranger", "xgboost").
  meths <- if (requireNamespace("rpart", quietly = TRUE)) c("glm", "rpart") else "glm"
  fit <- psave(treat ~ age + educ + race + married + nodegree + re74 + re75,
               data = lalonde, outcome = ~ re78,
               ps.methods = meths, prog.methods = meths)
  fit
  summary(fit)

  # hand off to MatchIt (canonical explicit call):
  m <- MatchIt::matchit(treat ~ age + educ + race + married + nodegree +
                          re74 + re75,
                        data = lalonde, distance = fit$ps)
  # or, reusing the stored formula and data (no retyping hazard):
  m2 <- psave_match(fit)
}
}
